{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Humans, dogs and cats are all capable of performing acts because they are capable of intentional states.",
    "Conversely, trees and rocks are not agents, since they are not capable of intentional (mental) states and thus, deliberate actions.",
    "Stones may change color or acquire moss, and trees may grow leaves, but these do not happen as the result of an action on the part of the rock or the tree [8].",
    "Other scientific views examine Nietzsche's prospect of the mind and its relationship to nature in the context of human agency.",
    "In Nietzsche's approach to the causal efficacy of conscious mental states, Doyle contends that Nietzsche proposes a naturalist but non-eliminativist account of mind, denying that consciousness is intrinsic to the mental states [9]."
  ],
